---
/**
 * Accordion Simple (tanpa button tag)
 * Gaya Neo-Brutalism minimal: klik header (div) untuk toggle konten.
 */
---

<div x-data="{ open: null }" class="w-full max-w-2xl mx-auto divide-y divide-gray-200 dark:divide-zinc-700 border border-gray-200 dark:border-zinc-700 rounded-lg bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900">
  <!-- Item 1 -->
  <div class="overflow-hidden">
    <div
      role="button"
      @click="open === 1 ? open = null : open = 1"
      class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer px-4 py-3 text-gray-800 dark:text-white font-medium transition-colors"
    >
      <span>What is Alpine.js?</span>
      <svg
        :class="open === 1 ? 'rotate-180' : ''"
        class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="2"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      >
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
      </svg>
    </div>

    <div
      x-show="open === 1"
      x-collapse
      class="px-4 pb-2 py-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed"
    >
      Alpine.js is a minimal JavaScript framework that lets you write declarative interactivity
      directly in your HTML.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Item 2 -->
  <div class="overflow-hidden">
    <div
      @click="open === 2 ? open = null : open = 2"
      class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer px-4 py-3 text-gray-800 dark:text-white font-medium transition-colors"
    >
      <span>Can I use it with Tailwind CSS?</span>
      <svg
        :class="open === 2 ? 'rotate-180' : ''"
        class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="2"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      >
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
      </svg>
    </div>

    <div
      x-show="open === 2"
      x-collapse
      class="px-4 pb-2 py-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed"
    >
      Yes! Alpine.js and Tailwind CSS are often used together for lightweight, modern interfaces.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Item 3 -->
  <div class="overflow-hidden">
    <div
      @click="open === 3 ? open = null : open = 3"
      class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer px-4 py-3 text-gray-800 dark:text-white font-medium transition-colors"
    >
      <span>Is Alpine.js reactive?</span>
      <svg
        :class="open === 3 ? 'rotate-180' : ''"
        class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 transition-transform duration-200"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="2"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      >
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
      </svg>
    </div>

    <div
      x-show="open === 3"
      x-collapse
      class="px-4 pb-2 py-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 leading-relaxed"
    >
      Absolutely! Alpine.js provides reactivity similar to Vue or React, but is much lighter.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
